It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Fiske II was born in 1290, in Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom as the son of Hugh Fiske I. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1317, in his hometown, at the age of 27, and was buried in Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1290–1317":"1290–1317","1315–1348":"1315–1348","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Laxfield, Mid Suffolk District, Suffolk, England":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Laxfield, Suffolk, England":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1290–1317":"1290–1317","1315–1348":"1315–1348","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1305":"1305","1348":"1348","1315":"1315","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1317":"1317","Laxfield, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Laxfield, Mid Suffolk District, Suffolk, England":"Laxfield, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuninga